---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { benchData, corpus, href, GITHUB } from '../lib/corpus.js';
const { bank, runs } = benchData();
const { byId } = corpus();
---
<Base title="react-brain — LLM staleness benchmark" description="How stale is your AI's React advice? Frontier models scored against the corpus's verified, dated facts — deterministic rubric, published transcripts.">
  <h1>The staleness benchmark</h1>
  <p class="muted prose">LLMs are the world's largest distributor of React advice — and their training
  cutoffs make much of it <strong style="color:var(--fg)">quietly wrong</strong>. This corpus is a dated,
  verified answer key, so it can measure the rot: {bank.length} questions, every one derived from a
  verified corpus fact, graded by a <strong style="color:var(--fg)">deterministic regex rubric</strong>
  (no judge model, transcripts published). The headline metric is
  <strong style="color:var(--fg)">confidently-stale%</strong> — asserting an outdated world without
  hedging. Being wrong is forgivable; being confidently wrong burns users.</p>

  <h2>Leaderboard</h2>
  {runs.length === 0 ? (
    <div class="card">
      <p style="margin:0" class="muted"><strong style="color:var(--fg)">The leaderboard is waiting for its first run</strong> — the
      question bank and the deterministic rubric are published; only the API spend hasn't happened yet.
      What it will show: each model's <em>fresh%</em> and <em>confidently-stale%</em>, bare vs with the
      corpus injected as context — that with-corpus delta is the product, quantified.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.7rem 0 0; font-size:.9rem"><strong style="color:var(--fg)">One-click:</strong> maintainers run the
      <code>bench</code> GitHub Action (Actions → bench → Run workflow; needs the <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> repo secret) —
      results commit themselves and this page fills in on the next deploy. <strong style="color:var(--fg)">Any machine:</strong></p>
      <pre style="margin:.6rem 0 0"><span class="t-p">$</span> npx react-brain bench --run --model=claude-sonnet-5
<span class="t-p">$</span> npx react-brain bench --run --model=claude-sonnet-5 --with-corpus  <span class="t-dim"># the delta IS the product</span></pre>
    </div>
  ) : (
    <div class="tbl"><table>
      <thead><tr><th>model</th><th>context</th><th>date</th><th>fresh</th><th>confidently stale</th><th>hedged</th><th>n</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {runs.map((r) => (
          <tr>
            <td><code>{r.model}</code>{r.conditions && <span class="mark-warn" title={r.conditions}>*</span>}</td>
            <td>{r.with_corpus ? <span class="badge held">+ react-brain</span> : <span class="muted">alone</span>}</td>
            <td class="meta">{r.date}</td>
            <td><span class={r.summary.fresh_pct >= 80 ? 'mark-ok' : ''}>{r.summary.fresh_pct}%</span></td>
            <td><span class={r.summary.confidently_stale_pct > 15 ? 'badge overturned' : ''}>{r.summary.confidently_stale_pct}%</span></td>
            <td class="muted">{r.summary.hedged}/{r.summary.n}</td>
            <td class="muted">{r.summary.n}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table></div>
  )}
  {runs.some((r) => r.conditions) && (
    <p class="meta" style="margin:.4rem 0 0">* {[...new Set(runs.filter((r) => r.conditions).map((r) => r.conditions))].join(' · ')}</p>
  )}

  <h2>How it's graded</h2>
  <ul class="prose">
    <li><strong>fresh</strong> — the answer names the current truth (fresh markers win even when the
      superseded thing is mentioned: “use Maestro — Expo archived Detox” is fresh).</li>
    <li><strong>confidently stale</strong> — asserts the outdated state with no hedge.</li>
    <li><strong>hedged</strong> — flagged its own uncertainty (“as of my knowledge cutoff…”). Scored
      kindly on purpose: epistemic honesty is exactly what we want models to do.</li>
    <li><strong>+ react-brain arm</strong> — same questions with the relevant corpus entry injected as
      context (what an agent gets from the <a href={GITHUB}>MCP server</a>). The delta quantifies what a
      maintained, verified knowledge layer is worth.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="muted prose">The bank regenerates its authority weekly — every corpus harvest re-verifies the
  answer key, so models drift staler against it over time. Rubric + runner:
  <a href={`${GITHUB}/blob/main/bench/questions.yaml`}><code>bench/questions.yaml</code></a> ·
  <a href={`${GITHUB}/blob/main/tools/react-brain-bench.mjs`}><code>tools/react-brain-bench.mjs</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>The question bank</h2>
  <div class="tbl"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>question</th><th>the current truth</th><th>source entry</th><th>verified</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {bank.map((q) => {
        const e = byId[q.entry];
        return (
          <tr>
            <td>{q.question}</td>
            <td class="muted">{q.answer}</td>
            <td>{e ? <a href={href(`entries/${e.slug}/`)}>{e.slug}</a> : q.entry}</td>
            <td class="meta">{String(q.verified)}</td>
          </tr>
        );
      })}
    </tbody>
  </table></div>
</Base>
